The Effect of Mental Health and Sleep on College Students' Academic Performance¶

Sneha Sureshanand & Ananya Vepa¶

Introduction¶

College students face an immense amount of pressure as they look to prepare themselves for their careers. This pressure manifests itself in different ways for students with two of the biggest ones being mental health and sleep habits. Mental health is one of the most influential factors in the way a college student functions especially when considering the fact that “more than 60% of college students met the criteria for at least one mental health problem” during the 2020-2021 school according to the Healthy Minds Study and highlighted by the American Psychological Association (Abrams, 2022). With such a significant amount of students struggling with their mental health, we questioned whether students’ academic performance is likely to be impacted in some way and to what degree. We were interested in seeing how students struggling with things like depression, anxiety, and stress balanced school on top of dealing with their mental health and understanding the degree to which their performance is affected because of these problems. Additionally, sleep, or lack thereof, is also known to be a fallout of the pressure that students face. As they look to do well in classes and juggle many of the other things they are working on, students tend to sacrifice sleep in order to have more time in the day. Knowing this, we were interested in seeing how this sacrifice and general sleep habits of students play a role in students’ academic performance.

The article by the American Psychological Association is linked here.

In this tutorial, our purpose is to understand how students’ average sleep and mental health problems such as depression, anxiety, and stress influence academic performance as measured by GPA. By using the SleepStudy dataset (which will be explained further in the Data Collection section), we were able to clean the data to perform exploratory analysis and then develop two models, a linear regression model and a random forest model. The linear regression model will be used to identify the degree to which each of the mental health problems(depression, anxiety, stress) and amount of sleep affect GPA and if there is a linear relationship between the predictors and the response (GPA). The random forest model will be used to further examine whether or not there is a relationship between mental health problems and sleep vs GPA that can be portrayed by a machine learning model.

Cleaning and Modifying the Data¶

The first step to cleaning the data is eliminating any rows that have null values. The reason that we do this is because null values prevent machine learning algorithms from creating accurate models. The missing data can cause bias when estimating parameters in the model as the model may not have enough information accurately create a value/coefficient. If the dataset has a sufficient amount of samples, we can just remove the row/column in which there is a null value. Consider removing row if there's one or more null value, and consider removing a column if there are several null values (over 255). However, only do this if there is a sufficient enough of data after dropping all the null values, otherwise you may risk underfitting the model since there is not enough data to effectively train the model. If you do not have enough data to delete null rows/columns, consider replacing the null values with an arbitrary value. For instance, this can include filling in a null value in a numerical column with 0.

Before conducting our exploratory analysis, we realized that we wanted to see the effect of the time people go to bed on the amount of hours of sleep they get. The fields 'WeekendBed' and 'WeekdayBed' represent the time people go to sleep. However, in both of these fields, the time is represented in decimal format. Also, if a person goes to bed after midnight that day, the hour is marked as 24 + the number of hours past midnight, which is an invalid time. For instance, if they go to bed at 1:30 am on a weekday, the 'WeekdayBed' field will read '25.5'. To do a proper time-series analysis, we have to convert these fields from decimal to datetime format. To do so, we first go through all the values in the 'WeekendBed' column and if the decimal time is greater than 24, we change the decimal to that value minus 24 to get the actual hour. We then append "am" to a newly created 'WeekendAMPM' column that tells whether the time represents morning or afternoon. If the time is within the 24 hours, its decimal value is retained and the time at which they go to bed is marked as "pm", since none of the data showed that people went to bed prior to 21.5 (9:30pm). We repeated the process for the "WeekdayBed" column.

Data to retrieve minimum time at which people go to bed is shown above - demonstrated by summary stats of 'WeekendBed' and 'WeekdayBed' columns

In [6]:
# Converts invalid hours like 25:45 to correct time and adjusts am/pm value
ampm = []
# Goes through all the values in the 'WeekendBed' column
for i in range(0, len(df['WeekendBed'])):
    # If the decimal time is greater than 24, we change the decimal to that value minus 24 to get the actual hour.
    if df['WeekendBed'].iloc[i] >= 24:
        df['WeekendBed'].iloc[i] = (df['WeekendBed'].iloc[i] - 24)
        # Append "am" to tell that the time represents morning
        ampm.append('AM')
    else: 
        # If decimal time is within the day, append "pm" to tell that the time represents night
        ampm.append('PM')
# Creates a new field that represent whether the time people go to sleep on weekends is am or pm
df['WeekendAMPM'] = ampm

ampm.clear()
# Goes through all the values in the 'WeekdayBed' column
for i in range(0, len(df['WeekdayBed'])):
    # If the decimal time is greater than 24, we change the decimal to that value minus 24 to get the actual hour.
    if df['WeekdayBed'].iloc[i] >= 24:
        df['WeekdayBed'].iloc[i] = (df['WeekdayBed'].iloc[i] - 24)
        # Append "am" to tell that the time represents morning
        ampm.append('AM')
    else: 
        # If decimal time is within the day, append "pm" to tell that the time represents night
        ampm.append('PM')
# Creates a new field that represent whether the time people go to sleep on weekdays is am or pm
df['WeekdayAMPM'] = ampm

The following code converts the decimal time in the 'WeekendBed' and 'WeekdayBed' columns to a string in the format hh:mm:ss.

In [7]:
temp = []
# Goes through all the values in the 'WeekendBed' column
for x in df['WeekendBed']:
    # Stores int (left hand side of the decimal) as the hour
    hrs = int(x)
    # Converts decimal to get the number of minutes
    mins = (x*60)%60
    # Converts decimal to get the number of seconds
    secs = (x*3600)%60
    # Appends the time in hh:mm:ss format to a list
    temp.append("%d:%02d:%02d" % (hrs, mins, secs))
# The 'WeekendBed' field is replaced with values in the hh:mm:ss time format
df['WeekendBed'] = temp

temp.clear()
# Goes through all the values in the 'WeekdayBed' column
for x in df['WeekdayBed']:
    # Stores int (left hand side of the decimal) as the hour
    hrs = int(x)
    # Converts decimal to get the number of minutes
    mins = (x*60)%60
    # Converts decimal to get the number of seconds
    secs = (x*3600)%60
    # Appends the time in hh:mm:ss format to a list
    temp.append("%d:%02d:%02d" % (hrs, mins, secs))
# The 'WeekdayBed' field is replaced with values in the hh:mm:ss time format
df['WeekdayBed'] = temp

Convert the newly adjusted 'WeekendBed' and 'WeekdayBed' columns from string to a datetime format. This will allow us to properly construct timeseries graphs as the time will be read as a time value and not a string. If the time is read at a string, it would be difficult to show values over time as it will be registered as categorical data with hundred of different categories since each "time" will be its own. However, by converting it to datetime format, the data will be read as a continuous variable instead of a discrete/categorical one, which allows us to better understand values relative to eachother.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

To begin our exploration, we will start by looking at the summary statistics for a few different variables in order to gain a quick and simple understanding of the data.

Looking at the summary statistics of DepressionScore, it can be seen that there is a mean of 5.20 which means that on average, the students in the sample feel depression at a fairly low degree. However, with a standard deviation of 6, it is understood that is a somewhat high degree of variability in this measurement as the degree to which students are depressed is spread out and this values for the observations are a bit far from the mean rather than being clustered around it. This shows that students face varying degrees of depression that must be accounted for as their academic performance is analyzed.

The summary statistics of AverageSleep show that on average, students sleep around 7.67 hours per night. This is an optimal amount of sleep according to a study published by the National Institute of Health (NIH) which found that "adults should sleep 7 or more hours per night on a regular basis to promote optimal health" (Watson et al., 2015). For further information on sleep for optimal health, the study can be found here. As seen by the first quartile, 75% of college students get at least 7.43 hours of sleep per night. This means that most college students tend to get the proper amount of sleep to maintain their health. This maintenance of their health can seep into other aspects of their life such as academics, which we will be exploring later on. While there is some variability with this variable having a standard deviation 0.96, it seems that the average sleep that students get is still fairly clustered around the mean as this standard deviation is relatively low when considering the range of values in this dataset. Since the observations for AverageSleep are mostly clustered around the mean, it can be understood that most students tend to get an optimal amount of sleep to maintain good health.

The two graphs below show weekend and weekday bedtimes versus the average hours of sleep a student gets as differentiated by AM and PM. On the left side of the graphs are times after midnight and the right sides are times before midnight. When looking at the two graphs, it can be seen that there is no clear difference between going to bed early or late (before or after midnight) during both weekdays and weekends. In both instances of weekdays and weekends, the average hours of sleep that students get is vertically clustered on either end of the charts. This means that regardless of what time students go to bed in either instance, there is no clear impact of bedtime on the amount of sleep they get. In order to verify this, we ran summary statistics and found that the difference in the average hours of sleep between AM and PM bedtimes for both weekdays and weekends was not more than hour. This very slight difference made us feel that there was not a significant enough amount of variability to use these variables in our analysis.

After performing this exploratory analysis, we wanted to more specifically understand the correlation between the variables to see how to most appropriately build our model by creating a correlation matrix with the seven variables we spent time investigating. There are two key points that we wanted to bring up from this correlation matrix. The first was that WeekdaySleep and AverageSleep are seen to be very highly correlated with a correlation coefficient of 0.92. While this seems intriguing, we wanted to note that this high value comes from the fact that AverageSleep is derived from WeekdaySleep so it is to be expected that these two are correlated in this way. The second point is the negative/low correlations between GPA and variables like DepressionScore, AnxietyScore, StressScore, and AverageSleep. When we were exploring the data, we expected there to be some correlation between these factors so these negative/low correlation coefficients were surprising to us. Because of this, we decided to explore those four variables further to understand why this was case. After creating histograms to look at the distributions of these four variables, we found that DepressionScore, AnxietyScore, and StressScore all had skewed distributions and AverageSleep's distribution was normal. The skewness of these three variables was causing an issue in the way their correlationn to GPA was calculated, so we thought it would be important to normalize the distributions in some way. This normalization will be further discussed in the Hypothesis Testing section.

Hypothesis Testing¶

After researching, we found a study conducted by the American Psychological Association that stated “more than 60% of college students met the criteria for at least one mental health problem”. As a result, we wanted to see whether mental health conditions and the amount of sleep students get affects their academic performance. Based on the data we had, we decided to measure students academic performance based on their GPA. However, in our exploratory analysis' correlation matrix, we found that there was very little correlation between stress score and gpa, depression score and gpa, anixety score and gpa, and average sleep and gpa. We wanted to further evaluate the situation to see if there was truly no significant impact of sleep/mental health conditions on academic performance and decided to conduct hypothesis tests.

Multiple Regression Model¶

First, we decided to create a multiple regression model. In this model, we will use StressScore, DepressionScore, AnxietyScore, and Average Sleep as predictors and GPA as a response variable. However, from the histograms of stress score, depression score, anxiety score, and average sleep in the exploratory analysis, we found that stress score, depression score, and anxiety score portrayed a skewed distribution. Before conducting a linear regression, we first have to make sure none of the assumptions are violated. These assumptions are:

  1. Linear Relationship: there must be a linear relationship between the independent and dependent variable
  2. Independence: The residuals should be independent
  3. Homoscedasticity: The residuals should have a constant variance
  4. Normality: the model should exhibit a normal distribution

Linear Regression Assumptions

However, since the data appears to be skewed for 3 of the predictors, the normality assumption is violated. In additon, we constructed the residual plots for the 4 predictors in the figure below. The plots for stress score, depression score, and anxiety score appear to be cone-shaped instead of randomly distributed along the x-axis, which shows that the homoscedasticity assumption is violated as well as there is not a constant variance in the residual plot. Also, in the regression plots in the exploratory analysis that show the relationship between gpa vs the 4 predictors individually, there is no majorly linear relationship, which violates the linear relationship assumption.

To make the data less skewed and represent a more normal distribution, we can perform a transformation on the skewed predictors. There are several transformation that we should consider. Below are 3 commonly used transformations and when we should use them.

  1. Log tranformation:
    • Only transforming predictors:
      • Should be performed when the linear relationship assumption is violated but all other assumptions hold true. Non-linearity should be the ONLY violation. This transformation will linearize the relationship between variables.
    • Only transforming response:
      • Should be performed when the normality and constant variance (homoscedasticity) assumptions are violated. This transformation will linearize a relationship and also give a more constant variance amongst error terms.
    • Transforming predictors and response:
      • This transformation should be considered when most or all assumptions of linear regression are violated. Transforming the predictors will fix the non-linearity issue, and transforming the y valies will fix the constant variance violation.
  2. Reciprocal transformation:
    • Should be used for data that portrays a positive skew. This transformation will reverse order amongst values that have the same positive or negative value
  3. Square root trasnformation:
    • This tranformation should be performed when variance is proprotional to the mean.

For the purpose of our hypothesis test, we will perform a log transformation on both the predictor and response variables since close to all linear regression assumptions are violated. This tranformation will resolve the most issues in comparison to the other transformations listed above.

To prevent -infinity values, use a log(x+1) transformation instead of log(x). As x approaches 0, log(x) can approach -infinity

To perform this test, we will set the following null and alternative hypothesis where each β represents one of the predictors:

H0: β1 = β2 = β3 = β4 = 0

Ha: At least one of these β’s is not 0

We will be using a α = 0.05 in this test, so if the p-value outputted by the regression model is less than 0.05, we will reject the null hypothesis at the 5% significance level.

Note: For stress score, depression score, anxiety score, and gpa, we will be using the log transformed fields

Now since the p-value of all the predictors are less than 0.05, we can reject our null hypothesis at the 5% significance level. This means that at least one of the coefficients (β1, β2, or β3) is significant in explaining the variation in the response (GPA). However, the R-sq value is 0.109 which means that only 10.9% of the variation in gpa can be explained by the regression model with stress score, depression score, and anixety score as predictors. This is a relatively low number, so the model does not effectively explain the relationship between the data.

Random Forest Model¶

To further test our hypothesis, we created a random forest model using the random forest classifier that was imported at the start the tutorial. We chose the random forest model over the decision tree model for a key reason of accuracy. By adding adding additional randomness when growing trees by splitting on a random subset of features in which it searches for the best feature, random forest allows trees to become decorrelated. In doing so, random forest reduces the overfitting problem that often occurs with decision trees and lessens the variance, leading to greater accuracy. For more information on the tradeoffs between random forest and decision tree models, this link provides more insight.

In this model, the x variables are logStressScore, logDepressionScore, and logAnxietyScore. We chose to use the log transformed values for these three variables in order to both maintain consistency from the linear regression model and to ensure that the normally distributed values were used in the model as to use more accurate correlation values to logGPA. Although AverageSleep was used as one of the variables in the linear regression model, we felt that it would be better to not include it in here because of it's high p-value of 0.455. The lack of correlation to logGPA that this shows makes it a somehwat irrelevant variable in our analysis and this irrelevance can negatively impact the accuracy of the model.

We decided to create a train/test split of 70% to 30% since this is a common split used in data science. When selecting our hyperparameters, we chose to use n_estimators, max_features, and min_samples_split. For n_estimators, we gave options of 5, 10, 50, 100, 150, and 200 to test how mayn decision trees should be created in order to produce the most effective model. Because the default value for this hyperparameter is 100, we thought it would be beneficial to give values both above and below this to see how the number of estimators impacts the accuracy. When deciding to choose max_features as a second hyperparameter, we were thinking about the idea that if all featture are considered in all of the splits, the random forest will then have identical trees. To avoid this problem, we provided values of sqrt, log2, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, and 1.0 so that the model could select the proportion of features that would yield the most accurate results. Finally, we chose to include min_samples_split as a hyperparameter to decide thet minimum amount of samples needed to split a nonterminal mode. A value that is too high can result in underfitting as it can restrict a model from learning relationships and a value that is too low can result in overfitting as it can lead to less generalization of the model. We provided the options of 2, 4, and 6 to accomodate various samples sizes and determine which would result in the most accurate random forest model. While there are other hyperparameters, we felt that these 3 would most significantly impact the model's accuracy and felt that they would be best to consider.

To choose the best hyperparameters, we ran GridSearchCV with a 10-fold cross validation in order to test all possible combinations of the hyperparameters to determine which was actually the best in terms of model accuracy. We chose GridSearchCV over RandomizedSearchCV because we wanted to try out all possible hyperparameters to find the optimal set rather than only trying a fixed number of hyperparameter settings and leaving space for there to be a higher degree of inaccuracy in the model than necessary. After running this GridSearchCV, we were able to find that the optimal combination of hyperparameters for the model was an n_estimators value of 100, max_features value of sqrt, and min_samples_split value of 6. These chosen hyperparameters were used when the random forest regressor was run to predict values based on the test data for the x variables.

After predicting these values, the mean squared error (MSE) was calculated between the test data for logGPA (y variable) and the predictions from the test data of the x variables. The mean squared error was chosen because it is a common and useful evaluation method for regression models and random forest can be considered a regression algorithm. After calculating the mean squared error, the value was found to be 0.0093. A value close to 0.0 indicates that all predicted values match the expected values exactly. This means that a lower MSE is better and shows a higher accuracy of the model. The value of 0.0093 is low and close to 0.0 so we can say that our random forest model led to accurate predictions.

# X is set to the predictors
X = df[['logStressScore', 'logDepressionScore', 'logAnxietyScore']]
# y is set to the response variable
y = df['logGPA']
# Sets test/train data where 70% is training and 30% is test
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=1)

# Provides various potential input parameters so that model can test out which combination works best
rf_params = {
    'n_estimators': [5, 10, 50, 100, 150, 200],
    'max_features': ['sqrt','log2', 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1.0],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 4, 6]
}

rf_model = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=1)
# Performs grid search cross validation on random forest model with provided model paramaters as inputs
grid_search = GridSearchCV(rf_model, rf_params, cv=10)
# Trains grid_search model with train data
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
# Obtains the optimal hyperparameter values
print(grid_search.best_params_)
hyperparameters = list(grid_search.best_params_.values())

Conclusion¶

After performing this analysis, we can see that mental health factors such as depression, anxiety, and stress are all related to students' academic performance as measured by GPA. Through the linear regression model and the p-values of DepressionScore, AnxietyScore, and StressScore all being less than the 5% significance level, it can be said that each of these variables have a relationship to GPA. We can also say that AverageSleep doesn't impact GPA based on thet p-value. However, the low R-squared value of 0.109 shows that this linear regression model doesn't explain the relationship between the data very well. WIth this being said, the high accuracy of the random forest model with a mean squared error of 0.0093 shows that there is definitely some relationship between the data that can be accuractely portrayed by the model. Overall, it can be said that the factors of DepressionScore, AnxietyScore, and StressScore impact overall academic performance through GPA in some way. While this trend isn't necessarily linear, it can be important to know that there is an effect on GPA based on these variables which could be further investigated to determine the specific relationship.
